The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             The City Diary
                A 32-year-old man, Bimal Agarwal, was arrested for allegedly impersonating former police commissioner Tushar Talukdar and demanding money from celebrities. The resident of Mukundapur called up singer Saikat Mitra posing as Talukdar and asked him to donate Rs 10,000 to a needy person sent by him. Mitra called the cops on learning that singer Banasree Sengupta had been duped the same way.     Sunil Shaw, 22, and his uncle Rajesh Shaw, 40, were killed at Halisahar, near Naihati, on Thursday morning when the motorcycle they were riding skidded. The two were thrown off the vehicle and run over by a truck. In another accident, five persons were injured after a Maruti Omni collided with an Ambassador plying in the wrong direction on New Town Road. The driver of the Ambassador has been arrested.    A walk for peace and harmony will be organised on December 7 at 11am from the Old Park Street Cemetery to Allen Park on Park Street through Rawdon Street, Short Street, Loudon Street, Hungerford Street, Wood Street and Camac Street.    The hearing of Ashok Todis bail plea continued in the high court on Thursday. Lawyers representing Rizwanur Rahmans family and the CBI opposed the petition. The petition will be heard again on Friday. The Supreme Court will hear on Friday a petition moved by the accused cops challenging the high court order cancelling their bail.    Power supply may be affected between 10am and 1pm on Friday in Baranagar, Gopal Lal Tagore Road, Bhattacharjee Para, Palpara, Bonhoogly, TN Chatterjee Street, Tobin Road, Noapara, Neogipara, SP Banerjee Road, Victoria Road, Belghoria Police Quarters, Dakshineswar, Alambazar and other areas because of maintenance by CESC.    Calcutta University will introduce a full-time M.Ed course in collaboration with Indira Gandhi National Open University from 2009. The course will be offered in distance learning and conventional modes.                                                                                                                                                                 
